    "excerpt": "A U.S. credit card was just the entry point. What I actually built is a global financial identity that does not depend on a single system — not backup, but recoverability.",
    "geoSummary": "A U.S. credit card was just the entry point. What I actually built is a global financial identity that does not depend on a single system — not backup, but recoverability.",
    "modelLabNumber": 1,
    "modelName": "Global Financial Identity",
    "modelStatus": "experimental",
    "wordCount": 597,
    "content": "<div class=\"doc-meta\">\n  <p><strong>Category:</strong> Finance</p>\n  <p><strong>Model Status:</strong> Experimental</p>\n  <p><strong>Confidence:</strong> Medium</p>\n  <p><strong>Last Updated:</strong> 2024-11-05</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>People often ask me:</p>\n<blockquote><p>\"Why get a U.S. credit card?\"</p></blockquote>\n<p>My usual answer: because I wanted to build a second financial identity.</p>\n<p>But later I realized the real answer is not America.</p>\n<p>It is:</p>\n<p><strong>I do not want my life to depend on a single financial system.</strong></p>\n\n<hr />\n\n<h3>It Started with a Frozen Account</h3>\n<p>In high school, I received funds from a problematic source and nearly all my Taiwan bank accounts became unusable.</p>\n<p>What worried me most was not the money.</p>\n<p>It was:</p>\n<blockquote><p>If I need access to funds in the future, do I have any other options?</p></blockquote>\n<p>That was when I first understood:</p>\n<p>Any system with only one entry point can become a <strong>Single Point of Failure</strong>.</p>\n\n<hr />\n\n<h3>I Started Building a Second Financial System</h3>\n<p>Many people get U.S. credit cards for:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li>Rewards</li>\n  <li>Miles</li>\n  <li>Sign-up bonuses</li>\n</ul>\n<p>That was not my focus.</p>\n<p>What I cared about was:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li>U.S. credit history</li>\n  <li>U.S. bank accounts</li>\n  <li>U.S. brokerages</li>\n  <li>U.S. payment capability</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Together, they represent one thing:</p>\n<p>I began to have a second financial infrastructure that can operate independently.</p>\n\n<hr />\n\n<h3>Later, Beyond the U.S.</h3>\n<p>After building a U.S. financial identity, I did not stop.</p>\n<p>I started building in:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li>United States (US)</li>\n  <li>Hong Kong (HK)</li>\n  <li>United Kingdom (UK)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Not because I live there.</p>\n<p>Not because I plan to immigrate.</p>\n<p>But because:</p>\n<blockquote><p>Every mature financial market I add is one more option.</p></blockquote>\n<p>I am not collecting bank accounts.</p>\n<p>I am reducing my dependence on any single financial system.</p>\n\n<hr />\n\n<h3>But I Am Not Building a Backup</h3>\n<p>Many people assume I am building a backup.</p>\n<p>I am not.</p>\n<p>I do not use all financial systems at once in daily life.</p>\n<p>What matters is:</p>\n<blockquote><p>I know that if I ever need to, I can start over.</p></blockquote>\n<p>What I pursue is not redundancy.</p>\n<p>It is <strong>Recoverability</strong>.</p>\n\n<hr />\n\n<h3>Internationalization Is Not About Travel</h3>\n<p>Many people think internationalization means:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li>Using cards abroad</li>\n  <li>Travel</li>\n  <li>Working overseas</li>\n</ul>\n<p>I prefer a different definition.</p>\n<p>Internationalization means your financial capability no longer exists in only one country.</p>\n<p>Your income can be cross-border.</p>\n<p>Your investments can be cross-border.</p>\n<p>Your assets can be cross-border.</p>\n<p>Then your financial identity should be cross-border too.</p>\n\n<hr />\n\n<h3>I Still Trust Banks</h3>\n<p>People ask: \"So you do not trust banks?\"</p>\n<p>No.</p>\n<p>I still use banks and still trust they work most of the time.</p>\n<p>I just do not believe any single system will never fail.</p>\n<p>Banks change policies.</p>\n<p>Companies collapse.</p>\n<p>Platforms shut down.</p>\n<p>Even countries can change the rules.</p>\n<p>The point is not predicting which one will break.</p>\n<p>It is:</p>\n<blockquote><p>When one fails, do you still have other options?</p></blockquote>\n\n<hr />\n\n<h3>Current Model</h3>\n<table class=\"doc-table\">\n  <thead>\n    <tr><th>Field</th><th>Content</th></tr>\n  </thead>\n  <tbody>\n    <tr><td>Model Name</td><td>Global Financial Identity</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>Core Principle</td><td>Build multiple independently operating financial identities — not to collect more products, but to reduce dependence on any single financial system.</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>Current Assumptions</td><td>Credit takes time to build; financial identity is a long-term asset; different jurisdictions offer different capabilities; internationalization means more options, not more accounts.</td></tr>\n    <tr><td>Failure Cases</td><td>Collecting accounts for the sake of collecting; maintaining too many relationships without real need; assuming cross-border systems eliminate all risk; ignoring compliance requirements across jurisdictions.</td></tr>\n  </tbody>\n</table>\n\n<hr />\n\n<h3>Research Queue</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li>How many financial identities does one person actually need?</li>\n  <li>How do you reduce the complexity of cross-border financial management?</li>\n  <li>Can financial identity be allocated like an investment portfolio?</li>\n  <li>Will global financial identity become personal infrastructure for the future?</li>\n</ul>\n\n<hr />\n\n<p>A credit card is not the goal.</p>\n<p>A bank is not the goal.</p>\n<p>What I am building is a person who <strong>does not depend on a single financial system</strong>.</p>\n\n<hr />\n\n<p><em>Model Lab is an ongoing research series. Each article is just one case study of a model in evolution.</em></p>",
